# ===========================================================================
# .dockerignore  —  files Docker EXCLUDES from the build context.
#
# WHY this matters: when you run `docker build` or `docker compose up --build`,
# Docker sends the entire build context (everything in the folder) to the
# Docker daemon before the first RUN instruction executes. Without this file,
# that includes node_modules (GB of binaries), DB data files, and secrets.
#
# Consequence: without .dockerignore a simple `docker build` can upload
# hundreds of MB before doing anything useful. With it, only the ~1 MB of
# source files and configs travel across the pipe.
#
# The pattern rules are identical to .gitignore.
# ===========================================================================

# The biggest offender: contains OS-specific compiled binaries (e.g. .node
# files, native addons). We run `bun install` INSIDE the image instead, which
# produces the correct Linux binaries for the container's CPU/OS.
node_modules

# Compiled TypeScript output — we run source directly with Bun.
dist

# PostgreSQL bind-mount data — multi-GB of binary DB files, never needed.
data

# .env contains real secrets (passwords, URLs). The Docker image must NOT bake
# them in — they are injected at runtime via `environment:` in compose or
# docker run -e. If the image contained .env, pushing it to a registry would
# leak the secrets permanently (layers are content-addressed, not deleteable).
.env
.env.*

# Git internals (can be large in repos with history).
.git
.gitignore

# Log files from dev sessions.
*.log

# OS noise.
.DS_Store
